 Compare the performance of the three models you just trained. Are there any meaningful differences in performance? 
Explain, in your own words, why these models have (or do not have) different performances.

There was a big difference in the performances of each model. Model A was trained on raw unnormalized features with no one-hot encoding and only achieved a 25.2% test accuracy.
Without normalization, the features are on very different scales, and it is nearly impossible for the network to learn effectively.
Model B added normalization, but no one-hot encoding and accuracy went up to 68.6%. Putting all the features on the same scale allows the gradient descent to move more smoothly.
Model C had both normalization and a one-hot encoding of 'State' variable, getting an accuracy of 72.3%. This increase in accuracy is because
with one-hot encoding, each state is treated independently rather than the implied ranking of label-encoding. 
